Let's now do another demonstration of the curriculum that we went through way back in fundamentals, but we're going to do it with our upgraded techniques. Now, before we jump into the demonstration, there are a few nuances about the technique that we really need to be aware of. First of all, back then, It was enough just to find some groups and to start chunking information in some basic ways. But now we've started to understand how questioning can affect the way that we view information and the type of processing that we can do. So it's no longer enough just to create groups and to have chunks. Instead, we need to have the best chunk possible. And that may not necessarily be the objective best chunk possible, but it needs to be the chunk that we feel the most comfortable with. And that means that the chunk needs to feel logical and intuitive. And I'm going to go through a flow chart in terms of how we know whether something is logical and intuitive because those two words are actually very, very important and a lot of people misunderstand them. So the goal here is to use that importance-based questioning in order to find the best possible chunk. And often you'll see that there are multiple possible chunk structures that are comparing against each other. And so what I'll do in this demonstration is I will go through and I will talk out loud my thought process. And you will see that I am comparing multiple chunk structures against each other. And note the wording I use there. I'm not just comparing different chunks with one another. I'm comparing different chunk structures with one another. And I'll go into that a little bit more later when you see it. Now, another thing is that because of the fact that this demonstration will have a lot of nuanced points in it, you'll get to see my thought process and how I process this information, but you're not going to pick up on a lot of those nuances if you don't already have some experience with this technique. So if you're coming to this video straight after watching the Ascent One videos and you're fresh off that boat, then I would recommend that you actually get a little bit of experience first, using the technique the best way that you have understood it so far, at least just for a two or three hour practice block, and reflect and do at least just one cope cycle on the pertinent issues and the problems and the difficulties that you face, the areas where you are uncertain about. Because if you watch this video without having done that, If it were me, if I know I've already watched the video and then I go through and I feel like, hmm, that video could actually be helpful again, I would feel a lot less likely to watch that one hour video all over again. So to get the most value out of your experience from watching this the first time around, it's going to be a lot better if you give it a go first, make a couple mistakes. You don't have to practice for like a... Whole week first, just maybe a couple of hours of making some good solid mistakes and reflecting, and then come back to this video, and then you'll see how my thought process might be subtly very different from yours. But again, if you haven't made that mistake first, it might completely just fly under your radar, and the biggest value that this video can give you could just be completely lost. So if you've had that experience, feel free to go ahead. If you haven't pause now, go back and we'll see you again soon. And if you're still here, presumably you've already had that experience and we can keep going. The important part that I want to really focus this on is the standard to which I hold myself to when I'm comparing chunk structures. And that's the thing that I want you to really focus on is the standard and the level to which I'm pursuing creating the ideal optimum chunk structure. I want you to pay close attention to not just the technique that I'm using, but how far I pursue and persist that logical and intuitive standard of chunking. Often when students are really struggling with a technique and they're feeling that their chunks are not giving them the retention or the mastery of knowledge that it's supposed to give them, and we do a deep diagnosis, then we find that in most cases, it's not that they didn't have the right technique, it's that they didn't use the technique extensively enough and they didn't compare enough chunk structures with each other. So I want you to pay attention to that when we get into this demonstration. So without further ado, Let's get into it. So as before, we're just going to start here with the curriculum and as you already know, we've got the concepts list that we can use. So before in fundamentals, we got that very basic concepts list, we got that very basic chunk structure, and now we're going to take that to the next level. So here's what I'm going to do. The first time around when I'm going through the information, this could be a pre-study or a priming session, I'm going to make sure that I have a good importance-based method of chunking. Now, I mentioned that it has to be logical and intuitive, the chunks that we end up with. If your chunks are not logical and intuitive, it means that you're going to have to spend more time and effort and cognitive resources to memorize them. So think about it this way. The way that you chunk the information either makes sense to you logically and intuitively, and therefore it aligns with your prior knowledge structures and networks, and therefore you will perceive it as being logical and intuitive, and therefore you won't have to exert so much effort to memorize it. However, if your chunk structure does not align very closely with your prior knowledge, then you now need to spend additional effort to remember the chunk structure. So now we're adding more things for us to memorize. And if we forget that chunk structure, then the benefit of chunking it is reduced somewhat. So how do we know whether something is logical or intuitive? Well, here's a very key point is that just because something is logical doesn't mean that it's intuitive. The opposite of logical is obviously illogical. So if you think about an illogical chunk structure, that could be, for example, deciding to chunk it all based on the ones that have the letter G. So this one would have a letter G. This one's got a letter G. This one is G. Oh, this one has a letter G too. So you can see that this is a very meaningless method of chunking. It's not very logical. I mean, I guess it is. Logical in a way, but it's very clear to see that that's not going to have much of a beneficial effect on our memory. The chunks that are often given to you in a textbook tend to be logical. They always tend to be logical because if it wasn't, it would be illogical. You see where I'm getting at here is that most chunk structures you encounter are actually pretty logical. So it's not relevant really to think about whether the structure is logical or not. We have to think about it as whether it is logical and intuitive so that word intuitive is key what we're talking about there is what i just discussed the idea that it seems so obvious that you don't even have to memorize it so examples would be something like cause and effect before versus if you thought after that means that that chunk structure was intuitive if i said up versus Did you think down? In that case, that chunk structure is intuitive. We're always looking for chunk structures that make it seem as if it's so obvious that we don't even have to remember it. That's the ideal goal. It's not always possible to do that, especially for some subjects that are really, really technically heavy. However, it is possible in most cases and you'll surprise yourself. Even with really technically heavy topics, you can also make things more logical and obvious by relying on your prior knowledge in that domain. So it may not be obvious to someone else, but it could be obvious to someone that has a reasonable level of domain knowledge. So going back to my background in medicine, if someone said to me, history versus investigation versus then for a normal person, that may not really lead them anywhere. But for many medical people, there are only a few things that would logically and intuitively come after that. For example, management or treatment. And so this brings me to a very nuanced point. You'll notice that in the instructions on how to do the chunking, we talk about the idea that you should create chunks. First, you should look through the information and try to create some of the most obvious chunks. However, what I've noticed is that people take this a little too far and they're not just making the chunks that are really obvious, they are committing to chunks that may not actually be that obvious. So, for example, an obvious chunk structure like problem versus solution maybe, that would be something that is an obvious chunk structure. However, even though we could arrive at an obvious chunk structure, it doesn't mean that we need to, in fact we shouldn't, commit to it. Because that chunk is only a hypothesis that we are then going to validate through our inquiry anyway. If we commit to chunks based on the headings that are already in textbooks versus the chapter names and terminology that's already given to us, and we don't do the chunking independently, then that's going to make a chunk that is probably too technical, too terminology heavy, and therefore requires us to memorize it. It may not be intuitive enough and therefore we'll just forget the chunk structure. And it probably will not really include all of the relationships we want to demonstrate either. So we're going to have all of those spider webbing, waterfalling kind of structures where there are lots of relationships going everywhere. It's going to be a mess to try to consolidate because really they should have been chunked differently in the first place. This is something that is influenced by what we call framing bias. Framing bias being the way that the information is presented to you affecting the conclusions and opinions that you have of that information. So if it's given to you in the textbook in a certain way, we're likely to think about it in a very similar way. And that's why with the concepts list, we do it out of order. You should be aware of that process by now. But we can create our own framing bias if we take a list of words and then we chunk them too in depth with chunk structures that are not intuitive and obvious. then that is something that we call pre-chunking. And that is when chunks are created before the process of inquiry, before we ask the why is it important question. And the reason that that is an issue is because if you create the chunks before you asked the importance-based questions, then that is likely to make the chunks not importance-based. It's quite logical, right? However, now that you've already chunked it that way, it predisposes us to being biased and now we think about it in those same chunks, even if those chunks are not actually optimal. Pre-chunking is not necessarily always a bad thing. And in some cases, it can be an effective tool, but we have to make sure we're not committing to those chunks and we're only using the most obvious ones. So here is a bit of a flow chart. First we ask, is the chunk that we're thinking about logical? If it's not, don't chunk it. If it is, then is it intuitive and obvious? Again, do we feel like we are going to have to spend any effort to actually memorize and remember this chunk? Or is it so intuitive and obvious that really anyone with either no prior knowledge or just a small amount of domain knowledge would be able to kind of predict and guess that chunk? Really, it has to be obvious. If the answer is no, it is not, do not chunk it. And if in doubt, Do not chunk it. If it passes all of those checks, then we can move on to importance-based inquiry. However, even when we're going through and asking those importance-based questions, why is it important? How is it related? If we find that the way that we've chunked it is not aligned with the reason for importance, then we need to change the chunk. So when we're doing this, we will find that it is either aligned or it is not. And if it is not aligned, then we need to break the chunk. We need to re-chunk it a different way. And if it is aligned, then we can keep it. Most of the time, we will actually end up breaking it. So if we're gonna break it most of the time, why do we even do this step in the first place? Why even give us the risk of pre-chunking in the first place? Because it can actually help us to think about things a little bit more deeply. And I'm gonna demonstrate that very shortly. So let's start with the concepts list as usual, and I'll go through to make some of the obvious chunks that I feel like I could start with. Okay. So there are a few chunks that I think could be quite intuitive here. One is the idea of theory versus application. So going to application. And the other one, I could think about it in terms of practice, like practicing to get better at something. Practice leading to skills. And I could think about... I could potentially also add outcomes onto that as well. For example, retention and retrieval could be considered outcomes. I mean, it's a pretty small, if it is a chunk, it'd be a pretty small chunk because there's only two things in there. But it is quite logical. Practice to skills and skills lean to outcomes. That seems really logical. So I think I'll leave that for now because I'm not so convinced that I want to keep that in there. And there's also the idea of sort of there's clearly sort of things here in terms of self-management. So that seems like a pretty good one. Now, even if I feel that self-management is a relatively intuitive chunk, why am I not committing that down? Or why am I not committing, but why am I not even writing that down? Be